{
  "What is the primary function of blubber in marine mammals?": "",
  "To protect them from predators": "",
  "To provide insulation and energy storage": "",
  "To aid in digestion": "",
  "To help them swim faster": "",
  "Blubber is a thick layer of fat beneath the skin that serves as insulation against cold ocean temperatures and as an energy reserve. It also contributes to buoyancy and helps streamline the body for swimming.": "",
  "Which of the following is a baleen whale?": "",
  "Sperm whale": "",
  "Orca": "",
  "Bottlenose dolphin": "",
  "Humpback whale": "",
  "Humpback whales are baleen whales that use plates of baleen to filter small fish and krill from the water. Sperm whales, orcas, and dolphins are all toothed whales (odontocetes).": "",
  "How do marine mammals breathe?": "",
  "By absorbing oxygen through their skin": "",
  "By surfacing to breathe air through lungs": "",
  "By extracting oxygen from water in their mouths": "",
  "Through gills like fish": "",
  "Marine mammals are air-breathing animals with lungs, just like land mammals. They must return to the surface regularly to inhale air, and many species have blowholes on top of their heads to facilitate breathing.": "",
  "Which group of marine mammals includes seals, sea lions, and walruses?": "",
  "Cetaceans": "",
  "Mustelids": "",
  "Sirenians": "",
  "Pinnipeds": "",
  "Pinnipeds are a diverse group of fin-footed marine mammals that include seals, sea lions, and walruses. The name 'pinniped' comes from Latin words meaning 'fin-footed,' referring to their flipper-like limbs.": "",
  "What do baleen whales primarily eat?": "",
  "Large fish and squid": "",
  "Seabirds and turtles": "",
  "Seaweed and kelp": "",
  "Small organisms like krill and plankton": "",
  "Baleen whales are filter feeders that consume massive quantities of small organisms, primarily krill, copepods, and small schooling fish. They use their baleen plates to strain these tiny prey items from large volumes of seawater.": "",
  "Which marine mammal is known for its long migrations between feeding and breeding grounds?": "",
  "Harbor seal": "",
  "Manatee": "",
  "Sea otter": "",
  "Gray whale": "",
  "Gray whales undertake one of the longest migrations of any mammal, traveling approximately 10,000–12,000 miles round trip between their Arctic feeding grounds and warm-water breeding lagoons in Baja California, Mexico.": "",
  "What is a group of dolphins or whales called?": "",
  "A herd": "",
  "A flock": "",
  "A colony": "",
  "A pod": "",
  "A group of dolphins or whales is called a pod. Pods can range from a few individuals to dozens or even hundreds, and members often cooperate in hunting, raising young, and protecting one another from predators.": "",
  "Which marine mammal group includes manatees and dugongs?": "",
  "Fissipeds": "",
  "Sirenians are an order of fully aquatic, herbivorous marine mammals that include manatees and dugongs. They are gentle, slow-moving animals sometimes called 'sea cows' because they graze on seagrasses and aquatic vegetation.": "",
  "How do mother marine mammals typically feed their young?": "",
  "Young are independent feeders from birth": "",
  "By nursing them with fat-rich milk": "",
  "By regurgitating fish": "",
  "By leading them to plankton blooms": "",
  "Like all mammals, marine mammal mothers nurse their young with milk. Marine mammal milk is extremely high in fat (up to 60% in some species), which helps calves build blubber quickly for insulation and energy in cold ocean waters.": "",
  "What is one key difference between seals and sea lions?": "",
  "Seals are mammals and sea lions are not": "",
  "Sea lions have visible ear flaps while seals have only ear holes": "",
  "Seals live in freshwater and sea lions live in saltwater": "",
  "Sea lions cannot swim as well as seals": "",
  "One of the most visible differences is that sea lions (family Otariidae) have small external ear flaps, while true seals (family Phocidae) lack external ears and have only small ear holes. Sea lions can also rotate their hind flippers forward to walk on land.": "",
  "What is echolocation?": "",
  "A visual system adapted for deep-sea darkness": "",
  "A biological sonar system that uses sound waves to detect objects": "",
  "A navigational method based on the Earth's magnetic field": "",
  "A method of communication using body language": "",
  "Echolocation is a biological sonar system used by toothed whales and dolphins to navigate and locate prey. They emit clicks and interpret the returning echoes to determine the distance, size, shape, and speed of objects in their environment.": "",
  "What does the term 'cetacean' refer to?": "",
  "All species of seals and sea lions": "",
  "The order of marine mammals that includes whales, dolphins, and porpoises": "",
  "Marine reptiles such as sea turtles": "",
  "Any marine animal with flippers": "",
  "Cetacea is the scientific order that includes all whales, dolphins, and porpoises. Cetaceans are fully aquatic mammals that are divided into two suborders: Mysticeti (baleen whales) and Odontoceti (toothed whales).": "",
  "What is thermoregulation in marine mammals?": "",
  "The process of maintaining a stable internal body temperature": "",
  "The ability to change body color in response to temperature": "",
  "The regulation of water salinity within the body": "",
  "The mechanism for controlling swimming speed": "",
  "Thermoregulation is the process by which marine mammals maintain a consistent core body temperature despite living in cold ocean environments. They use adaptations like blubber, countercurrent heat exchange in blood vessels, and behavioral strategies to conserve or dissipate heat.": "",
  "What is the term for the comb-like filtering structure in the mouths of certain whales?": "",
  "Gill rakers": "",
  "Barbels": "",
  "Denticles": "",
  "Baleen": "",
  "Baleen is a keratinous structure (made of the same protein as human fingernails) that hangs in plates from the upper jaw of mysticete whales. It acts as a sieve to filter small prey like krill and fish from enormous mouthfuls of water.": "",
  "What does the term 'odontocete' mean?": "",
  "Filter-feeding whale": "",
  "Toothed whale": "",
  "Deep-diving seal": "",
  "Freshwater mammal": "",
  "Odontoceti is the suborder of cetaceans that have teeth rather than baleen. This group includes dolphins, porpoises, sperm whales, beaked whales, and orcas. 'Odonto' comes from the Greek word for tooth.": "",
  "What is a 'blowhole' in cetaceans?": "",
  "A sensory pit for detecting water pressure": "",
  "A specialized organ for producing sound": "",
  "An opening on top of the head used for breathing": "",
  "A gland that removes excess salt from the body": "",
  "A blowhole is the nostril opening located on top of a cetacean's head, which allows the animal to breathe without fully lifting its head above water. Baleen whales have two blowholes, while toothed whales have one.": "",
  "What does the term 'mysticete' refer to?": "",
  "Baleen whales": "",
  "Marine carnivores": "",
  "Fin-footed marine mammals": "",
  "Toothed whales": "",
  "Mysticeti is the suborder of cetaceans commonly known as baleen whales. The name comes from the Greek word 'mystax,' meaning mustache, referring to the baleen plates that hang from their upper jaws. This group includes blue whales, humpbacks, and right whales.": "",
  "What is a marine mammal 'stranding'?": "",
  "When a marine mammal becomes beached or trapped in shallow water": "",
  "When a marine mammal surfaces to breathe": "",
  "When a marine mammal loses its pod": "",
  "When a marine mammal migrates to a new location": "",
  "A stranding occurs when a marine mammal comes ashore and is unable to return to the water on its own, or is found floating near shore and unable to swim. Strandings can be caused by illness, injury, disorientation, or environmental factors like sonar disturbance.": "",
  "What is the 'melon' in a dolphin's head?": "",
  "A fat-filled organ that focuses and directs echolocation clicks": "",
  "A gland that produces oil for waterproofing": "",
  "A bone that protects the inner ear": "",
  "A structure in the brain that controls memory": "",
  "The melon is a rounded mass of fatty tissue found in the forehead of toothed whales and dolphins. It acts as an acoustic lens, focusing and directing the sound waves produced during echolocation so the animal can accurately detect objects in its environment.": "",
  "What is 'countercurrent heat exchange' in marine mammals?": "",
  "A way of cooling down by increasing blood flow to the skin": "",
  "A system where warm arterial blood heats cool venous blood to reduce heat loss": "",
  "The process of generating body heat through rapid swimming": "",
  "A method of heating water in their stomachs": "",
  "Countercurrent heat exchange is an arrangement in which arteries carrying warm blood from the body core run alongside veins carrying cold blood from the extremities. Heat transfers from the warm arterial blood to the cool venous blood, conserving body heat and preventing excessive heat loss through flippers and flukes.": "",
  "A researcher observes a whale swimming with its mouth open near the surface, taking in large volumes of water and then expelling it through the sides of its mouth. What feeding strategy is this whale most likely using?": "",
  "Suction feeding on the seafloor": "",
  "Echolocation-assisted hunting": "",
  "Filter feeding using baleen plates": "",
  "Cooperative bubble-net fishing using teeth": "",
  "This behavior describes filter feeding, which is characteristic of baleen whales. They engulf large volumes of water containing prey and then push the water out through their baleen plates, trapping krill and small fish inside their mouths.": "",
  "A pod of dolphins is observed working together to herd a school of fish into a tight ball near the surface before taking turns swimming through to feed. What is this an example of?": "",
  "Cooperative hunting behavior": "",
  "Territorial defense": "",
  "Migration preparation": "",
  "Solitary ambush predation": "",
  "This is cooperative hunting, a sophisticated social behavior seen in dolphins and orcas. By working together to corral fish into a bait ball, each individual increases its feeding efficiency compared to hunting alone, demonstrating the benefits of living in social pods.": "",
  "A marine biologist discovers that a population of North Atlantic right whales has declined to fewer than 350 individuals. Which factor is most likely contributing to this critically endangered species' decline?": "",
  "Genetic immunity to all diseases": "",
  "Introduction of a new predator species": "",
  "Entanglement in fishing gear and vessel strikes": "",
  "Overpopulation leading to food competition": "",
  "North Atlantic right whales are critically endangered, with entanglement in fishing gear (especially lobster pot lines) and collisions with ships being the leading causes of death. These slow-moving, coastal whales are particularly vulnerable because they often swim in busy shipping lanes.": "",
  "A sperm whale dives to over 2,000 meters deep and stays submerged for up to 90 minutes. Which physiological adaptation best explains how it can accomplish this?": "",
  "It stores extra oxygen in its muscles using high concentrations of myoglobin": "",
  "It has gills that supplement its lungs at depth": "",
  "It breathes small amounts of water at extreme depths": "",
  "It enters a state of complete metabolic shutdown": "",
  "Deep-diving marine mammals like sperm whales have extremely high concentrations of myoglobin in their muscles, which stores oxygen for use during prolonged dives. They also have higher blood volume, can collapse their lungs, and slow their heart rate to conserve oxygen.": "",
  "Rescuers find a group of 30 pilot whales stranded on a beach. One possible cause being investigated is nearby naval sonar exercises. How might sonar contribute to the stranding?": "",
  "Sonar removes oxygen from the water, forcing whales to surface near shore": "",
  "Intense sonar can damage hearing and disrupt navigation, causing disorientation": "",
  "Sonar heats the ocean water, making it uninhabitable": "",
  "Sonar attracts whales toward the shore as a food source": "",
  "High-intensity military sonar has been linked to mass strandings of cetaceans. The powerful sound waves can damage the inner ears of whales, disrupt their echolocation and navigational abilities, and cause panic responses that lead to rapid surfacing, tissue damage, and disorientation.": "",
  "A marine scientist records complex, repeating sequences of sounds from a male humpback whale during breeding season. What is the most likely purpose of these vocalizations?": "",
  "Communicating distress to nearby vessels": "",
  "Echolocating to find food in deep water": "",
  "Attracting females and establishing dominance through whale song": "",
  "Warning predators to stay away from the pod": "",
  "Male humpback whales produce long, complex songs primarily during the breeding season. These songs are believed to serve as mating displays to attract females and to establish dominance among competing males. All males in a population typically sing the same song, which evolves over time.": "",
  "The vaquita, a small porpoise found only in the Gulf of California, has fewer than 10 individuals remaining. What is the primary threat driving the vaquita toward extinction?": "",
  "Climate change raising water temperatures beyond their tolerance": "",
  "Oil spills contaminating their only habitat": "",
  "Bycatch in illegal gillnets set for another endangered fish, the totoaba": "",
  "Overhunting by local fishing communities for food": "",
  "The vaquita is the most endangered marine mammal in the world, driven to near extinction primarily by bycatch in illegal gillnets used to catch totoaba fish. The totoaba's swim bladder is highly valued in traditional medicine, and vaquitas become entangled and drown in these nets.": "",
  "A walrus is observed using its tusks to haul itself onto a floating ice platform. In addition to locomotion, what other function do walrus tusks serve?": "",
  "Filtering food from sediment on the ocean floor": "",
  "Establishing social hierarchy and defending against predators": "",
  "Sensing vibrations to locate prey under the ice": "",
  "Regulating body temperature by releasing excess heat": "",
  "Walrus tusks, which are elongated canine teeth, serve multiple functions beyond hauling out onto ice. They are used to establish dominance in social hierarchies, defend against polar bears and orcas, and maintain breathing holes in sea ice. Larger tusks generally indicate higher social status.": "",
  "A manatee is found in an inland freshwater spring during winter months. What is the most likely reason the manatee has moved to this location?": "",
  "To avoid predators found in the open ocean": "",
  "To find a mate during the breeding season": "",
  "To seek warmer water temperatures for thermoregulation": "",
  "To feed on marine algae unavailable in coastal waters": "",
  "Manatees are highly susceptible to cold stress because they have relatively low metabolic rates and little blubber compared to other marine mammals. During winter, they seek out warm-water refuges such as natural springs and power plant outflows, where water temperatures remain above 68°F (20°C).": "",
  "An orca population in the Pacific Northwest has been classified as endangered due to declining salmon runs, high toxin levels in their blubber, and increased boat traffic. A conservation plan is being developed. Which approach would best address the multiple threats facing this population?": "",
  "Restoring salmon habitat, regulating pollutants, and establishing vessel distance rules": "",
  "Introducing additional prey species from other ocean regions": "",
  "Relocating the orcas to a marine aquarium for protection": "",
  "Focusing solely on reducing boat traffic near the pod": "",
  "The Southern Resident orcas face interconnected threats that require a comprehensive conservation strategy. Restoring salmon runs addresses food scarcity, reducing pollutant discharge helps lower toxin accumulation in blubber, and enforcing vessel distance regulations reduces noise disturbance that interferes with echolocation and communication.": ""
}